[[File:Locmap-Haro-Boundary2.png|thumb|300px|right|Boundary Pass, along with [[Haro Strait]], connects the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]] and the [[Strait of Georgia]] along the international boundary between the [[United States]] and [[Canada]]. This map follows the [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] definitions. Major islands are named.]] '''Boundary Pass''' is a [[strait]] that runs for about {{convert|23|km|mi}} along the boundary between the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] and the [[Canada|Canadian province]] of [[British Columbia]]. It connects [[Haro Strait]] to the south with the [[Strait of Georgia]] to the north.
The [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] defines its northern boundary as a line extending from East Point on [[Saturna Island]] to Alden Point on [[Patos Island]]. Its southeastern boundary is a line from Alden Point on Patos Island to Point Hammond on [[Waldron Island]] then from Sandy Point on Waldron Island to Charles Point on [[Stuart Island (Washington)|Stuart Island]]. Its southwestern boundary is a line connecting Turn Point on Stuart Island to Point Fairfax on [[Moresby Island (Gulf Islands)|Moresby Island]]. Its western boundary is a line running from Pelorus Point on Moresby Island to Wallace Point on North [[Pender Island]] then to Tilly Point on South Pender Island then from Teece Point on South Pender Island to Taylor Point on Saturna Island.<ref>{{gnis|1509727|Boundary Pass}}</ref>
