{{Infobox valley | name = Grand Bara | other_name = | photo = Baadha Wayn (Grand Bara).jpg | photo_caption = The Grand Bara Desert <!-- MAP --> | map = | map_image = | map_caption = <!-- Location --> | location = | country = [[Djibouti]] | region = [[Ali Sabieh Region]] | region1 = [[Arta Region]] | region2 = [[Dikhil Region]] | state = | district = | city = | relief = | label = | label_position = | coordinates = {{coord}} | coordinates_ref = <!-- Statistics --> | elevation = | elevation_m = | elevation_ft = | elevation_ref = | length = | length_mi = | length_km = | length_orientation = | length_note = | width = | width_mi = | width_km = | width_orientation = | width_note = | area = | area_mi2 = | area_km2 = 103 | depth = | depth_ft = | depth_m = | type = | age = | border = | topo = | traversed = | river = <!-- Below --> | footnotes = | embed = }}
The '''Grand Bara''' ({{lang-so|Baadha Wayn}}), '''Bara Wein''' or '''Bada Wein''', is a desert in southern [[Djibouti]]. It consists of large areas of sand flats, with sparse, semi-desert and desert grasses and scrub vegetation.<ref name="Aean">{{cite book|last1=Rod East, International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources, Antelope Specialist Group |title=Antelopes: East and Northeast Africa |date=1988 |publisher=IUCN |isbn=2880329426 |page=25|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=2KRJAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> A road built in 1981 passes through the area, connecting the capital [[Djibouti City]] with the south.<ref name="Wimer">{{cite book|last1=Carim|first1=Enver|title=Middle East Review|date=1983|publisher=World of Information|page=86|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=idbsAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> Prior to the arrival of the French, the extremely arid interior was inhabited primarily by the [[Issa (clan)|Issa]] [[Somali people|Somali]].
==Geography== The Grand Bara and Petit Bara are the remains of dried up lake beds. They form vast arid plains in the centre of Djibouti and mark the delimitation of the volcanic part of the country from the sedimentary part. The clay of which they are formed is poorly drained and water collects here in the rainy season and this is followed by the growth of grasses.<ref name=Alwan>{{cite book|author1=Alwan, Daoud Aboubaker|author2=Mibrathu, Yohanis|title=Historical Dictionary of Djibouti |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b9drQ9YeLxcC&pg=PA19 |year=2000 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=978-0-8108-3873-4 |page=19}}</ref>
Djibouti has few paved roads; it has been estimated that there are about {{convert|2900|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} of roads, only about 12% being paved, and fewer than half being serviceable throughout the year. In 1981, a road across the Grand Bara was built, linking the capital with the south. It is about {{convert|40|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} long.<ref>{{cite book|author=Eur|title=Africa South of the Sahara 2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1KBP7QbalX0C&pg=PA348 |year=2002 |publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-1-85743-131-5|page=348}}</ref>
==Ecology== The Grand Bara is part of the [[Ethiopian xeric grasslands and shrublands]] ecoregion. Large mammals occurring in this area include the [[Beira antelope]] (''Dorcatragus megalotis''), [[Dorcas gazelle]] (''Gazella dorcas''), [[Soemmerring's gazelle]] (''Gazella soemmerringii''), [[Salt's dik-dik]] (''Madoqua saltiana'') and [[gerenuk]] (''Litocranius walleri''). Few [[Beisa oryx]] (''Oryx beisa'') remain after great hunting pressure. The [[Berbera gerbil]] (''Gerbillus acticola'') is endemic to this region as are [[Arnold’s leaf-toed gecko]] (''Hemidactylus arnoldi'') and the [[northern sand gecko]] (''Tropiocolotes somalicus''). [[Archer's lark]] (''Heteromirafra archeri'') is the only endemic bird species.<ref name="WWF">{{WWF ecoregion|id=pa1305 |name=Ethiopian xeric grasslands and shrublands |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>
==Climate== The heavy rainfall affected the Grand Bara. As a Result the Plain floods in July and September. The climate of the Grand Bara limits the number of animals living permanently in these extreme conditions. {{Weather box|location = Grand Bara |metric first = yes |single line = yes |Jan high C = 27 |Feb high C = 28 |Mar high C = 30 |Apr high C = 32 |May high C = 34 |Jun high C = 38 |Jul high C = 38 |Aug high C = 37 |Sep high C = 35 |Oct high C = 32 |Nov high C = 29 |Dec high C = 27 |Jan low C = 17 |Feb low C = 19 |Mar low C = 21 |Apr low C = 23 |May low C = 26 |Jun low C = 28 |Jul low C = 27 |Aug low C = 26 |Sep low C = 24 |Oct low C = 20 |Nov low C = 18 |Dec low C = 17 |source 1 = The World Weather Channel |date=December 2015}}
