[[File:HerbertOgden.jpg|thumb|Herbert Gouverneur Ogden]]
''' Herbert Gouverneur Ogden''' (1846-1906) was an [[United States|American]] [[geographer]], [[topographer]], [[civil engineer]], and [[cartographer]].<ref>http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2012/11/21/lighting-the-way/</ref>

==Biography==
Ogden was born on April 4, 1846, in [[New York City]]. In 1863 he joined the [[US Coast and Geodetic Survey]], where he originally worked on the defenses of [[Washington DC]] during the [[American Civil War]]. The following year he went to map the coast of [[North Carolina]] for the [[Union Navy]]. In 1865 he went on an expedition to [[Nicaragua]], and in 1870 to [[Panama]] and the [[Darién Gap|Darien]]. He married in [[Brooklyn]], in 1872, and co-founded the [[National Geographic Society]] in 1888. In 1893 he mapped the [[Alaska]]-[[Canada]] border. He was a vice-president of the National Geographic Society.

Ogden passed away on February 25, 1906. Resting place in Oak Hill Cemetery, Washington DC.<ref name="Grave" />

