{{Coord|20|55|0|N|17|11|0|E|display=title}} {{Infobox spring | name = Soborom | photo = | photo_width = | photo_caption = | map_image = {{Location map | Chad | lat_deg = 20.916667 | lon_deg = 17.183333}} | map_width = | map_caption = | name_origin = | location = {{Flag|Chad}} | elevation = 850m | coordinates = | coords_ref = | hot_spring_type = | height = | duration = | frequency = | discharge = | temperature = between {{convert|22|and|88|C|F|abbr=on}} | depth = }}
'''Soborom Hot Springs''' is a [[geothermal]] field located close to the northwestern rim of [[Tarso Voon|Tarso Voôn]] volcano in [[Chad]]. It is situated on the eastern flank of [[Emi Koussi]] at an altitude of 850 meters (20°55'0"N, 17°10'60"E).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.getamap.net/cartes/chad/borkou-ennedi-tibesti/_soborom/|title=Soborom Carte (Plan), Photos et la meteo - (Tchad): printemps (s) - Latitude:20.9167 and Longitude:17.1833|website=fr.getamap.net}}</ref>
The field consists of a dozen [[hot springs]], where water emerges at temperatures ranging between {{convert|22|and|88|C|F|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Hughes and Hughes|1992|p=1–3}}<ref name=soborom>{{cite web |title=Soborom |publisher=Wondermondo |url=http://www.wondermondo.com/Countries/Af/Chad/Tibesti/Soborom.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119024359/http://www.wondermondo.com/Countries/Af/Chad/Tibesti/Soborom.htm |archivedate=January 19, 2013 |deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ci/books?id=VLjafeXa3gMC&pg=PA319&lpg=PA319&dq=Soborom+Hot+Springs&source=bl&ots=j8oQ1AXbo9&sig=bC2Et28U9-Z3dUKBxbfV27JtW_w&hl=fr&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Soborom+Hot+Springs&f=false|title=A Directory of African Wetlands|first=R. H.|last=Hughes|date=10 December 1992|publisher=IUCN|via=Google Books}}</ref> The field also contains [[mud pools]] and [[fumaroles]] that vent noxious gases including [[sulfur]]{{dn|date=October 2017}}<!--Sulfur isn't a gas. This could mean either hydrogen sulfide or sulfur dioxide, two chemicals with very different properties-->.<ref name="readersnatural" />
The springs are considered to have healing powers - the word Soborom purportedly means "water which heals" in one of the local languages. It is common for the [[Toubou people]] as well as others from this part of [[Sahara]] to visit this natural resort for a few days to heal diseases such as [[dermatitis]] and [[rheumatism]].<ref name="readersnatural">{{Cite book|title=Natural Wonders of the World|publisher=Reader's Digest Association, Inc|year=1980|isbn=0-89577-087-3|editor-last=Scheffel|editor-first=Richard L.|location=United States of America|pages=350|quote=|editor-last2=Wernet|editor-first2=Susan J.|via=}}</ref> They bathe in one of the less hot pools which has a temperature of about 42°C. Visitors have made some simple utilities in the pools such as headrests made of flat stones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wondermondo.com/Countries/Af/Chad/Tibesti/Soborom.htm|title=Soborom geothermal field and Yerike hot spring - Wondermondo|website=www.wondermondo.com}}</ref>
